{"slug": "spell", "root": "spell", "category": "act", "gloss": "a formula of magical words", "definition": "A spell is a formula of words that works magic — the utterance that does something. In the game it is the most basic unit of action: a card you cast.", "history": "Old English *spell* meant simply 'a saying, a story, a sermon' — *gospel* is *gōd-spell*, 'good news,' and spelling out letters is the same word. The 'magic formula' sense is the youngest of the three, sharpening around 1580. Magic made *spell* its most fundamental term, which is why it shows up in over 8,000 rules texts but barely a hundred flavor texts: in Magic, 'spell' is mechanics, not story.", "def_sources": [{"label": "Etymonline, s.v. spell", "where": "Etymology reference"}, {"label": "the corpus", "where": "Corpus"}], "commentary": "'Spell' carries the oldest assumption in the anthropology of magic: that words themselves are operative. James Frazer treated the spell as pseudo-science, a mistaken belief that saying makes it so. S. J. Tambiah's 'The Magical Power of Words' overturned that condescension, arguing that spells are performative acts whose force is ritual and social rather than a botched theory of cause. Don C. Skemer's *Binding Words* grounds the point materially, showing how written formulae worked as objects and practices, not failed physics — so the field now studies what a spell *does* in its setting rather than whether its speakers were being irrational.", "commentary_sources": [{"label": "S. J. Tambiah, 'The Magical Power of Words'", "where": "Reference", "url": "https://doi.org/10.2307/2798500", "url_kind": "doi", "abstract": "Looking closely at a Sri Lankan exorcism ceremony, anthropologist Tambiah argues that spells and magic words \"work\" not because they're bad science but because of how ritual speech is performed - the repetition, rhythm, and formula make the words feel powerful, the same way a wedding vow or courtroom oath does real social work just by being spoken aloud."}, {"label": "Don C. Skemer, Binding Words", "where": "Reference", "url": "https://www.psupress.org/books/titles/0-271-02722-3.html", "url_kind": "publisher", "abstract": "Skemer studies small handwritten charms called textual amulets - strips of parchment inscribed with prayers or words of power that medieval people wore on their bodies or carried for protection - showing how these objects blurred the line between everyday religious devotion and magic."}, {"label": "RenaissanceMagicDB, s.v. ligatura", "where": "RenaissanceMagicDB"}], "is_keyword": false, "etymology": {"lang": "Old English", "origin": "Old English spell 'saying, story, sermon' (Proto-Germanic *spellam)", "first": "before 900; 'incantation' sense c. 1580", "note": "'Gospel' is gōd-spell ('good news'); spelling out letters is the same word (a 'reading-out'). The magic sense is the youngest of the three.", "hook": "Gospel, spelling, and spellcasting are one word."}, "essay": null, "sources": ["Etymonline (Douglas Harper)", "Wiktionary", "classical lexica (Lewis & Short, LSJ, Bosworth–Toller)", "Ted's historical-magic DBs (WitchcraftStudiesDB, AgrippaDOP, MedievalMagicDB)"], "stats": {"flavor_total": 97, "oracle_total": 8202, "in_flavor_cards": 93, "in_oracle_cards": 6349, "name_match_count": 31, "by_variant": {"spell": 6851, "spells": 1444, "spellcasters": 2, "spellcasting": 2}, "first_year": 1993, "colors": {"G": 1202, "R": 1565, "U": 2226, "B": 1100, "W": 1223, "C": 503}, "by_year": {"1993": 2, "1994": 20, "1995": 34, "1996": 34, "1997": 59, "1998": 61, "1999": 68, "2000": 81, "2001": 76, "2002": 43, "2003": 57, "2004": 93, "2005": 94, "2006": 82, "2007": 72, "2008": 92, "2009": 60, "2010": 57, "2011": 77, "2012": 63, "2013": 108, "2014": 160, "2015": 195, "2016": 143, "2017": 188, "2018": 207, "2019": 174, "2020": 319, "2021": 462, "2022": 656, "2023": 596, "2024": 825, "2025": 555, "2026": 601}}, "cards": [{"id": "d63f4eeb-3fa5-4e65-8414-e3fd3c03c128", "name": "Drudge Spell", "set": "HML", "s